I"G<p>The <a class="internal-link" href="/secondbrain/boltzmann-machine-is-a-universal-learning-machine">Boltzmann</a> <a class="internal-link" href="/secondbrain/kl-divergence-formalizes-difference-between-discrete-probability-distributions">distribution</a> is a <a class="internal-link" href="/secondbrain/joint-marginal-and-conditional-probabilities-are-primitives-of-probability-theory">probability</a> distribution of <a class="internal-link" href="/secondbrain/dynamical-systems-have-a-certain-anatomy">microstates</a> determined by the observed macrostate and the energies of microstates. For example, the Boltzmann distribution offers a probability distribution over the possible states of a gas in a container (i.e. location &amp; momentum of each <a class="internal-link" href="/secondbrain/particle-systems-populate-spaces-with-object-instances">particle</a>) given an observed temperature and knowledge about energies of possible microstates. Itâ€™s a physics-flavored <a class="internal-link" href="/secondbrain/argmin-and-argmax-formalize-optimization">optimization problem</a>.</p>
